The `.equals()` method, on the other hand, checks if the two strings are equal by comparing their byte arrays. This means it checks the exact sequence of bytes in both strings.

However, it's important to note that `==` and `equals()` have different behaviors:

1. `==` checks for object identity (whether two references point to the same object), while `equals()` checks for value equality (whether the objects contain the same data).

2. `==` can return true even when the objects are different because they may be different instances of the same class.

3. `equals()` will return true only when the objects are the same instance of the same class.

So, to compare two strings, you should use `equals()` instead of `==`. If you want to compare if two strings have the same content, use `==`. 

For example:

```java
String str1 = "Hello, world!";
String str2 = new String("Hello, world!");

if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("The strings are equal.");
} else {
    System.out.println("The strings are not equal.");
}
```

